e and the native/settler divide. Despite erasure and racism, nonmilitary Black residents consider Hawaiʻi their haven, describing it as a place to "breathe" that offers the possibility of becoming local. Sharma's analysis of race, indigeneity, and Asian settler colonialism shifts North American debates in Black and Native studies to the Black Pacific. Hawaiʻi Is My Haven illustrates what the Pacific offers members of the African diaspora and how they in turn illuminate race and racism in "paradise."  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh2 aNational Endowment for the Humanitiesefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478093817?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478093817zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478093817/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA